Catupiry is a popular Brazilian cheese spread that is rich, creamy, and fluffy in texture. It has a slightly sweet and sour flavor and is commonly used as a topping or filling for dishes like pizza, bread, crackers, and pastries.

Catupiry was invented by the Italian immigrant Mario Silvestrini in 1911 in SÃ£o Paulo, Brazil.

The name Catupiry is derived from Tupi-Guarani, the indigenous language of Brazil, and means 'excellent' or 'fantastic'.

Initially, Catupiry was produced manually by Silvestrini, but it soon became popular, and a small factory was set up to manufacture it in large quantities.

Currently, Catupiry is one of the most famous and iconic food brands in Brazil, and it is widely distributed throughout the country and in some international markets.
